{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503077","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503077"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:54:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:54:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1929"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1929","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1929"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.44,0.05,0.09,0.41,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1929"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50049"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1929","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1929"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1929"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35324"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"527"},{"type":"tags","id":"934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3168"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10913"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13902"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15027"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50049","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/50049"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 39-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of colicky abdominal pain, worse on the right side. The pain started intermittently but has become more severe and constant in the last few hours. He also reports a fever and some nausea. The patient has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his pulse is 90/min, blood pressure 124/90mmHg, temperature 38.4\u00baC, and his BMI is 35kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. Abdominal examination shows an area of tenderness in the right lower quadrant. A plain X-ray is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ureteric colic","Mesenteric adenitis","Pyelonephritis","Acute appendicitis","Crohn\u0027s disease"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical picture described in the stem fits well for a diagnosis of \u003Cstrong\u003Eacute appendicitis\u003C/strong\u003E. The patient\u0027s obesity might explain the paucity of signs on physical examination, in terms of obvious peritonitis. Appendicitis must be the presumed diagnosis until proven otherwise. In most circumstances - and certainly where the diagnosis is uncertain - the patient would have a CT scan. However, in this case a plain X-ray was performed and the only abnormality to be seen was the radio-opacity in the right iliac fossa (Image). When abnormal calcification is encountered radiologically within the abdominal cavity there are a variety of different causes to be considered:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECalcified lymph nodes\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERenal tract calculi\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFaecoliths\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECalcified cysts (eg hydatid)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPhleboliths\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGallstones\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVascular calcification\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis particular radiopacity is too lateral to be within the renal tract or a lymph node. It is most likely to be a calcified faecolith. A faecolith in the appendix increases the risk of perforation and was probably responsible for this episode of appendicitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUreteric colic\u003C/strong\u003E is a reasonable differential for unilateral colicky abdominal pain. However, it is unlikely that patients with uncomplicated ureteric colic will develop a fever unless pyelonephritis develops as a complication. If the patient had developed some complication associated with a ureteric stone, the area of tenderness would focus on the right flank. Some changes to urination would also be expected, including haematuria, frequency, urgency and dysuria. The area of calcification seen overlying the right ilium is too lateral to represent any lesion in the renal tract.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMesenteric adenitis\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare differential that can mimic acute appendicitis. It is also more commonly found in children. Mesenteric adenitis would not explain the presence of the radiopaque area shown on the X-ray.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPyelonephritis\u003C/strong\u003E more commonly presents with unilateral flank pain that is particularly tender on palpation of the kidney itself (right flank) rather than palpation of the right lower quadrant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECrohn\u0027s disease\u003C/strong\u003E may present similar to this patient however, a more common history would involve bowel changes and gradual and generalised abdominal pain perhaps brought on by a trigger such as physiological stress. It is unlikely that a patient would present so acutely and severely with the first episode of Crohn\u0027s disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Acute appendicitis typically presents with abdominal pain that increases in severity, frequency and localises to the right lower quadrant over days.","A faecolith appears as a radiopacity on abdominal x-ray. However, it is not a common cause of acute appendicitis."],"references":["Di Saverio S, Podda M, De Simone B, Ceresoli M, Augustin G, Gori A, et al. Diagnosis and treatment of acute appendicitis: 2020 update of the WSES Jerusalem guidelines. World J Emerg Surg. 2020;15:27. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32295644/","Ramdass MJ, Sing QY, Milne D, Mooteeram J, Barrow S. Association between the appendix and the fecalith in adults. Can J Surg. 2015;58(1):10\u20134. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4309758/#:~:text=It%20is%20generally%20accepted%20that,the%20presence%20of%20a%20fecalith."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35324"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1929"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"14413"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20539"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"14413","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/14413"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/acf55616-6a21-44f1-a9d2-cddebd78aa84.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/acf55616-6a21-44f1-a9d2-cddebd78aa84.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":355,"height":440}},{"type":"media","id":"20539","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20539"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ZncbWFxlCDN84GoD5ABkNE50CotgUB.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ZncbWFxlCDN84GoD5ABkNE50CotgUB.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":355,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35324","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/35324"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-06T21:06:01+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-06T21:07:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1929"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50049"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.